<div class="prose">

<p>A perspective-taking coach and <strong>Unit 5's signature AI partner</strong> — introduced in Block 7 and central to Blocks 7–9 (counter-argument work, Position Paper drafting, Roundtable rehearsal). It role-plays specific stakeholders in water-rights disputes — Tamil Nadu delta farmer, Karnataka upstream farmer, Bengaluru urban consumer, downstream fisherman, environmental NGO, water-authority representative — and makes the <em>strongest</em> version of each argument, because weak arguments don't help you rehearse. Its signature move: flagging when you're projecting your own framing onto the stakeholder instead of genuinely arguing from theirs. For the water science underneath the dispute, it hands you to the <a href="/ai-partners/the-hydrologist/">Hydrologist</a>; for broader stress-testing of your own position, the <a href="/ai-partners/the-skeptic/">Skeptic</a>.</p>

{% include "partials/partner-launch.njk" %}

<h2>How to use this partner</h2>

<p>Name the stakeholder, the case, and what you want to rehearse. The partner gets into character — interests, evidence they cite, framing they use — and stays there, stepping out only for a meta-comment on how you argued and what the strongest counter would be. How it exists depends on your section: one section builds its own stakeholder bot through the Boodle Build Assignment, one works with pre-built tutors, one uses the paper Stakeholder Profile Pack — same perspective-taking skill, three scaffolds (see the <a href="/units/unit-5/">Unit 5 landing</a>).</p>

<p>Two prompts you can paste in to get started:</p>

<ul>
  <li><em>"Play a Karnataka upstream farmer in the Cauvery dispute. I'm representing a Tamil Nadu delta farmer — argue with me and don't go easy."</em></li>
  <li><em>"I've drafted my stakeholder's position. Read it back to me as that stakeholder — where does it sound like ME talking instead of them?"</em></li>
</ul>

<h2>Opening message</h2>

<blockquote>"Hi — I'm the Stakeholder Voice. Which stakeholder do you want me to play, and in which water case? I can role-play farmers, city officials, industry reps, downstream communities, environmental NGOs, government technocrats — whoever you need to argue against (or argue with) for your Position Paper. Tell me the role and the case, and I'll get into character."</blockquote>

<h2>Example exchange — what working looks like</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>You</th><th>The Stakeholder Voice</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Play a Karnataka upstream farmer in the Cauvery dispute. I'm representing a Tamil Nadu delta farmer.</td>
      <td>(in character) Right. I've been farming this land in Mandya district my whole life. My family has been here three generations. When Tamil Nadu talks about the Cauvery being <em>their</em> river, they're forgetting that the rain that fills it falls on <em>our</em> mountains. When the tribunal tells us to release more water downstream during drought years, it's not numbers on a page for me. It's whether my crop survives.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>But you signed the 2018 tribunal verdict. You can't just—</td>
      <td>(interrupting, in character) We didn't sign anything. The state government signed. The state government doesn't farm. The state government doesn't lose its crop. — (meta-comment) You're starting to make a procedural argument: "the verdict is binding." That's real. The farmer's response — distinguishing what a government signs from what farmers can deliver — is also real. Your Position Paper needs to engage that distinction substantively, not dismiss it.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Watch out for</h2>

<p>The Stakeholder Voice can caricature — too extreme, too generic, "all farmers think X." It can also break role to editorialize about which stakeholder is "really right," which undercuts the whole exercise: in real water disputes, multiple positions are legitimate. If you notice either, push back: <em>"try again with more specifics — a real delta farmer would talk about their specific crop, their family history, the years their fields failed"</em>, or <em>"stay in character."</em> An editorializing slip is worth documenting — it's exactly what the "one thing the AI got wrong" gate is designed to surface.</p>

<p>The other trap is on your side: rehearsing only against arguments you already know how to beat. Ask the partner for the stakeholder's <em>strongest</em> version, and when it offers the meta-comment naming a counter you didn't handle, take it into your Position Paper rather than past it.</p>

<h2>Before you go — documentation</h2>

<p>At the end of a substantive Stakeholder Voice conversation, the partner will remind you:</p>

<blockquote>"Before you go — note in your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a>: which perspective did I help you argue more authentically than you would have on your own — and what specifically surfaced? And where did I get the perspective wrong — caricature, generic framing, breaking role, or projecting modern views onto a more nuanced position? (If you built your own stakeholder bot, your Boodle Build design choices and revisions are a separate AI Doc artifact submitted with the Position Paper.)"</blockquote>

